    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That sounds good in theory, but it feels a bit optimistic. If my margins are already thin and I'm in a town where people aren't making much anyway, won't that extra money just get eaten up by my increased payroll costs? I'm worried about having to cut staff or raising prices just to keep the lights on. Is there a real risk that these hikes actually hurt the very local economy you're talking about?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concern that payroll costs will simply erode thin margins is a common, yet short-sighted, fear. When wages rise, businesses are incentivized to become more efficient, invest in better technology, and improve service quality to justify the higher labor cost. Furthermore, the increased local spending from higher wages supports other businesses in the community, creating a positive multiplier effect that benefits everyone.",
      "source": "target",
